## 1. Preventive measures

- Operating system fully patched, automatic security updates enabled
  (nightly, reboot window 04:00 {{ timezone }} when required)
- SSH: key-based authentication only, root login disabled,
  password login disabled, access restricted to authorized users
- Firewall: default deny on all inbound traffic, only web ports
  (80/443) exposed
- Intrusion throttling: fail2ban active with escalating ban times
{% if paranoia_level == "high" %}
- Single Packet Authorization (fwknop): the SSH port is invisible to
  scanners and opens only for authorized, cryptographically verified
  requests, for {{ fwknop_open_seconds }} seconds at a time
{% endif %}
- Web server hardened: TLS enforced (auto-renewing certificates),
  security headers active, version disclosure disabled
- Application runs as an unprivileged system user

## 2. Data protection

{% if db_engine is defined %}
- Database engine: {{ db_engine }}
- Database bound to localhost only, verified unreachable from the internet
- Application database account restricted to least privilege
- Encryption at rest: documented per provisioning method (see appendix)
{% else %}
- No database on this server
{% endif %}

## 3. Backup and recovery

- Nightly encrypted backups at 0{{ backup_hour }}:{{ backup_minute }} {{ timezone }}
- Encryption performed on the server before upload, decryption key is
  held offline by {{ report_prepared_by }}, never stored on the server
- Destination: Backblaze B2 bucket with versioning, using an access key
  that has NO delete permission. Even a fully compromised server cannot
  destroy backup history
- Retention: {{ backup_retention_daily }} daily, {{ backup_retention_weekly }} weekly, {{ backup_retention_monthly }} monthly
- Backup success/failure monitored in real time
- Restore verification: performed monthly on isolated infrastructure

## 4. Detection and response

- System audit trail active: identity changes, privilege changes,
  SSH trust changes, scheduled task changes, binary tampering
- Ransomware early warning: mass file-change detection with immediate
  alerting
- Breach detection suite, three independent detectors:
  - Behavioral login verification (interactive SSH sessions must match
    an expected usage pattern)
  - Reverse-shell detection (shells attached to a network socket, or the
    application account spawning a shell)
  - Recon-burst detection (a session running a rapid series of system
    enumeration commands)
- Response mode: {% if watcher_mode == "active" %}automatic — offending
  session terminated and source blocked, after forensic evidence is
  captured{% else %}alert-only — immediate operator notification with
  captured evidence{% endif %}
{% if egress_lockdown | default(false) %}
- Egress lockdown active: outbound traffic default-denied except
  required service ports, refusing reverse-shell callbacks
{% endif %}
- All alerts delivered to the operations team in real time

